Hello developers.<br />I have been wondering after reading this part of the web storage spec: <a href="http://dev.w3.org/html5/webstorage/#cross-directory-attacks" class="postlink">http://dev.w3.org/html5/webstorage/#cross-directory-attacks</a><br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />Even if a path-restriction feature was made available, the usual DOM scripting security model would make it trivial to bypass this protection and access the data from any path.<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />How exactly could this kind of restriction be bypassed ? And more importantly, can it be done for cookies as well ?<br /><br />Thanks in advance.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=67">Jordan</a> — Sat Nov 28, 2009 7:13 pm</p><hr />
